FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - SOUTH AFRICA: (LIMPOPO) BOVINE, SEROTYPE SAT 3, OIE
****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 11 Dec 2015
Source: OIE, WAHID weekly disease information 2015; 28(51) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=19321


Foot-and-mouth disease, South Africa
------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 11 Dec 2015 from Dr Bothle Michael Modisane, Chief Director, Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Animal Production and Health, Pretoria, South Africa

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 8 Dec 2015
Date of confirmation of the event: 10 Dec 2015
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 10 Feb 2015
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] virus
Serotype: SAT 3
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1 (FMD-2015-SAT3-001): FMD-2015-SAT3-001, Thulamela, Limpopo
Date of start of the outbreak: 8 Dec 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 1200 / 14 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Cattle with clinical signs were detected in one diptank area in the FMD protection zone.
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 1.17 / 0 / 0 / 0
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: contact with wild species
Epidemiological comments: The outbreak occurred in cattle at one diptank within South Africa's FMD protection zone and therefore has no effect on South Africa's FMD free status.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country; quarantine; no vaccination, no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: vaccination in response to the outbreak(s); surveillance within containment and/or protection zone

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Agricultural Research Council - Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute (ARC - OVI) (OIE Reference Laboratory) / Cattle / liquid-phase blocking ELISA / 10 Dec 2015 / Positive
Agricultural Research Council - Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute (ARC - OVI) (OIE Reference Laboratory) / Cattle / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 10 Dec 2015 / Positive
Agricultural Research Council - Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute (ARC - OVI) (OIE Reference Laboratory) / Cattle / virus isolation / Pending

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since August 2013 to June 2014, South Africa reported to the OIE 13 outbreaks of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) caused by FMDV SAT 2 strain in Mpumalanga province. The event was resolved on 10 Feb 2015. See report and map at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000017240_20150224_143809.pdf.

Limpopo province shares international borders with districts and provinces of 3 countries: Botswana's Central and Kgatleng districts to the west and northwest respectively, Zimbabwe's Matabeleland South and Masvingo provinces to the north and northeast respectively, and Mozambique's Gaza province to the east. The province is the link between South Africa and countries further afield in sub-Saharan Africa. On its southern flank from east to west, the province shares borders with Mpumalanga, Gauteng, and North West (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limpopo).

For an interactive map showing all the outbreaks in the area, please go to http://tinyurl.com/ngwc4we, click on the territory of choice and zoom in.

A map of South Africa can be seen at http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/south_africa_map.htm. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3857426,2947.]
